AST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Carlos, Luis, Jesus, Jorge, Angel, Ramon, Francisco, Manuel, Raul, Ana.","Catalan: habitational name from a place in Barcelona province named Cardona. Its name dates from the pre-Roman period."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ramon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Raimundo .   See  <b>Raymond</b>   ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"VIII","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine pet form of   Vivien   and   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1354684,"age":10,"year":"1200","julianDay":2159351,"description":"The Christian territory controlled the Kingdoms of Aragon, Navarre, and Castile.","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"When Ramon VIII Folch de Cardona was born in 1190, in France, his father, Guillem \"el Rico\" Vizconde de Cardona, was 37 a